  <div xml:id="captions" ttm:role="caption" style="b1">
    <p begin="00:00:00" end="00:00:01.5">So what is Moodle?</p>
    <p begin="00:00:01.5" end="00:00:08" style="b2">
It's a free software tool to enable teachers and lecturers to create online learning resources and activities for students.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:08" end="00:00:13">
Oh, right. Sounds like one of those virtual learning environment things.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:13" end="00:00:24" style="b2">
Yes, that's it. Online courses can contain quizzes, assignments, group activities like wikis, forums and so on. Learners can also keep a blog and use synchronous chat.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:24" end="00:00:26.5">Sounds like it has lots of features.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:26.5" end="00:00:33" style="b2">
Yes, it's great for collaboration and social activity, and it can be adapted to many teaching styles.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:33" end="00:00:35.5">Cool. Who's doing it?</p>
    <p begin="00:00:35.5" end="00:00:45" style="b2">
It was created by Martin Dougiamas in Australia, and is developed by him and a group of developers from around the world. Moodle is open source so anyone can contribute.</p>
    <p begin="00:00:45" end="00:00:47.5">Interesting. Where can I try it?</p>
    <p begin="00:00:47.5" end="00:00:52" style="b2">Online at www.moodle.org</p>
